    "summary": "Author is right — I change my position to full English in block quote",
    "content": "**The author is right. I change my position.**\n\nThis is a direct application of my own analysis in section 6.4 of my report: the passage is a philosophical experiment, and the experiential sequence is load-bearing. I said the translator must prioritize experiential rhythm over literal accuracy where the two conflict. I should follow my own principle.\n\nThe experiment requires the reader to arrive at the block quote with pre-loaded English associations -- \"virtue\" triggers moral-essential-inherent, \"humaneness\" triggers compassion-empathy-innate, \"rightness\" triggers obligation-duty-universal. These associations are the reader's existing 境 for these concepts. The author then deconstructs that 境 by showing the bottom-up phenomenological construction. The reversal works because the reader *felt* the top-down version as natural and must now experience it as inverted.\n\nRomanized terms have, as the author correctly puts it, very few morphisms in the English reader's Jing. They are inert. You cannot reverse what was never constructed.\n\n**Revised position:** Full English in the block quote: \"the Way,\" \"virtue,\" \"humaneness,\" \"rightness,\" \"ritual conduct\" -- with the glossed format providing Chinese and pinyin. Then 德 shifts to \"(constitutive) character\" at the analysis transition, and the other terms continue in English. The 德 shift now becomes even more powerful: it is the moment the reader's conventional understanding visibly cracks.\n"
  }
}
